Paper Mario was especially good because that month was the perfect amount of time to get through it. Majora's Mask plays awfully on the Switch emulator though; hopped over to the 3DS Restored patch and it's an absolute revelation.

I will say, for as much as we all clown on Nintendo's slow classic game rollout, it is fun as a sort of retro game book club. Have quite enjoyed seeing others' Paper Mario and Majora's Mask playthroughs alongside my own!

I don't often feel like talking about my progress, but I get such a little rush every time I feel myself getting closer to formulating my own statements off-the-cuff. 😍

It's so fuckin cool when the whole reversed subject/verb order starts to click in your brain. If you literally translate bit to bit the statement is "We have grapes, of wine is made", so you learn pretty quickly how much thinking in English first will slow you down.
One of the earliest phrases Duo teaches you when it comes to relative clauses is "私たちはぶどうからワインを作りました", and it has such a fun rhythm to it that HAUNTS me months later lmao

We're coming up on four years since I dropped out. I know I shouldn't be keeping track but it's impossible to think of anything else when that hole remains unfilled. I don't even know if it counts as burnout anymore when it's lasted this long.

Please for the love of god let therapy and/or medication get me some kind of hobby that isn't just consumption. I miss drawing so much but I'll take anything at this point. I feel so incredibly aimless.
I don't like getting personal on main because it usually has terrible outcomes; that said I'm incredibly anxious and letting people know that feels important. It's been a fucking *YEAR*, gang.

My N64 controller from Nintendo should be arriving on Friday - I'm so excited to see how it handles modern games. How will the rumble feel? Can you rebind the button layout? If so - how will the C-buttons work? I'm genuinely very excited.

I still maintain (as with NES + SNES Online) that these games are presented incredibly weirdly; Nintendo have demonstrated historically that they have manuals for these games still - in some cases, the original PDFs! It'd go a long way if they were included here.

Per-game button mapping would be much appreciated though; doing advanced maneuvers in Star Fox 64 basically requires a claw grip if you're using the joycon. My muscle memory from 3D and Zero isn't helping either, lmao.

Loving the N64 games on Switch atm. Opening selection could've definitely been a little meatier, really hope the monthly updates return. Emulation seems fine to me - quite low-res with no anti-aliasing but I kinda dig the rawness! Input latency leagues ahead of Wii U, oh my god.

Shame this doesn't seem to be the Deluxe replacement I'd hoped for, but that's okay! I'm happy to know for myself and the devs seem super passionate and in touch with the interests of a VERY diverse fanbase, so I'm happy having chucked them the coin.

Only played a handful of minigames - Monkey Race felt fine, Bowling felt terrible (and individual character stats seem to be gone!), Monkey Target was as jank as expected with very little visual feedback. Kinda scared to try the rest honestly.

I hope patches fine-tune it a bit or I get more used to it, it's just... weird. Also funny thing - game feels like absolute ass on an official GameCube controller through USB, feels kinda nice on the PowerA GameCube-style wireless controller.

I died like 15 times on my first run of SMB1 Casual, where I'd managed to get it down to 0 on my Beginner runs of the original game very recently. Most of the time it felt like I'd suddenly lurch forwards when approaching an edge and there was no recovery.

Some stages it works fine, and may even be beneficial but others it feels infuriating to not be able to turn with quite the same level of precision. Most times it's an extra layer I have to think about and that impacts my reaction times.

Bought Banana Mania in the end because I wanted to feel out those changes to the controls. I think they've tried to emulate the octagonal gate from GameCube, but also added some easing between directions...? It feels a bit like pen smoothing on a graphics tablet. Really uncanny.

Anything else from Rare Replay is possible, I suppose; it'd be an amazing move if Microsoft used Perfect Dark on Switch as a goodwill token to lure people over for the new game on Xbox.

Veeeery intrigued to see if this Microsoft agreement extends to Diddy Kong Racing, I'm like 95% positive it will. Weird that Tooie wasn't confirmed just yet. Conker is probably completely off the table though, no way Nintendo are gonna let the young'ins stumble on THAT one.
Same deal for Excitebike 64 - which didn't even release on Wii VC the first go around. Nintendo must be inking some interesting deals behind the scenes...

Very curious what happens with Wave Race 64 as well! In the Wii version, all Kawasaki ads were replaced with DS/Wii logos, only for the original product placement to inexplicably return on Wii U! My guess is it'll be the latter or they'll just make the textures totally blank.
Anyway, I'm genuinely excited for people who've never experienced Yoshi's Story with rumble before to lose their minds over how needlessly excessive and strong it is
@AuralAce The gyro literally transforms those shooting minigames lmao. Such a great remake.

People are totally gonna see stuff like the positively lethargic text boxes in 50hz Ocarina and write off the games as having aged much worse than they needed to. The weirdest part is that I swear the GameCube version ran at NTSC speed with all the European languages intact...

At the very least, if you create a Nintendo Account and set the location to America, you can download the U.S. versions of the apps and then use them with your European NSO account. I've been doing the very same to play the Famicom and Super Famicom range. Still a hassle though!

Time investment tends to be more valuable than money to me... if I spend £1 on a bargain-bin title and find nothing of value or anything that compels me to keep playing after a couple of hours, I'll still feel like there was a waste of energy there. It's an odd phenomena.

Is it a £40 experience? God no - and neither was Star Fox 64 3D when I paid that price for it a decade ago. I love both of these games and will often defend a game's 'worth' against its price as a subjective matter, but there's no arguing against a dearth of content.

When it clicks, and especially when you're intimately familiar with the levels as score-attack games so frequently encourage you to be, there's a really fun 'flow state' of knowing when to divert your attention and digging deeper into the level as a result.

Even then, I definitely have to be in the 'right mood' to play it. If I'm feeling especially irritable or distracted then I'm not likely to give it the patience and attention that it demands. It's comparable to playing a really in-depth vehicle simulation, from my POV at least.

Having now watched the video - totally understand his POV and how it reflects the wider gaming populace. I still enjoy the game, but absolutely acknowledge I'm part of a niche minority who finds the frantic action of juggling my attention between screens to be more fun than most

I wanted to love you, NASA-grade EyeToy!! You were the chosen one!

One time my housemate was on their phone and raised their hand to their ear, which Peggle 2 took as an opportunity to immediately switch to buggy motion controls and seize up the cursor for a good few seconds. That was especially fantastic.

Accidentally played a few games of Halo online before realising it was acting as a mic - had to turn that off. Tried to use voice search on YouTube - didn't recognise it. Tried to play a demo of the Rabbids Kinect game - had absolutely no visual feedback or camera window.

We had to be careful not to say 'Xbox' too loudly in conversation, lest it read it as a command and lock up the system for a sec. Even then it would just randomly interpret casual phrases like 'oh that's weird' as 'Xbox, TV off'

Even the coolest stuff like the face recognition for profiles was a) more laggy than just selecting a profile manually and b) recognised the wrong people at the wrong times and switched accounts at random moments

The last month has been me slowly disabling features of the Kinect that were starting to get in my way until there was nothing to do but turn it off. As a big fan of niche hardware, this made me very very sad.

It's not unheard of either - slightly retouched assets from Splatoon and Mario Tennis: Ultra Smash were utilised in their Switch successors. I genuinely love Zero, but trying to port it would be way too much effort for how toxic that name has become. It's gotta stay behind.

I understand the desire; it clearly had a high budget, came to the system at a point long after most people had ditched it, and featured a steep learning curve for the controls. At this point however, Nintendo would be much better served repurposing the assets for a new game.

The fact that so many people assume Star Fox Zero can easily be ported to Switch just goes to show how misunderstood that control scheme was. The simultaneous cockpit view and gyro aiming were absolutely crucial for most stages - including the final boss.

Wario's sprite also manages to be this amazing mixture of grotesque and heroically muscular - probably his best depiction in the series! Reminds me a lot of the later Shantae games, come to think of it. https://t.co/sP0xDXk6gw

Wario Land 4 isn't my personal favourite, but I can absolutely see why it ends up on so many top game design lists. Looting a temple and then having to dash back through it once the final trap is set is such a genius concept, both thematically and mechanically. 💕

@SmagicSmarties It's definitely handy for games I was likely to pre-order/buy day one anyway! There's only a handful of Switch games at this point where I think I'd prefer to have the cart and lovely boxart, so I'll definitely get good use out of this offer

@scully1888 (also I realise now that I SLIGHTLY went askew on your original topic, but this whole furore has been on my mind since the service was first revealed and I kinda leapt at the opportunity to discuss it with someone who wouldn't just discard the idea of NES games outright)

@scully1888 I appreciate that my opinion is in the minority and many are outraged by the idea of even playing an NES game after abundant opportunities in the past, but every release can be someone's first! It's massively important to keep these games in circulation on legacy alone.

@scully1888 Yes, I totally agree!! It's also a much better demo experience than say, Smash's Masterpieces. By the same token, I'd love to pay a small premium to "keep" certain games after the servers go. That's where I think there's a bigger gulf between your collection idea and the reality.

@scully1888 Absolutely. 90% of critique I see is about the NES games being old and crusty and not worth any amount of money, which I feel is a crass generalisation, but the service isn't without it's objective drawbacks compared to the Virtual Console system.

@scully1888 I didn't quite realise this myself until my internet went down for most of April, and it struck me that those games were now gone. Made me much less reluctant to pick up the Castlevania Collection, where the games were more expensive but I at least feel a degree of ownership.

@scully1888 I will say that for as big of a fan of the NES Online service as I am, and feel the value is superb, an annual fee of £17.99 for access to a library that essentially has always-online DRM (bar the 7 day grace period) isn't quite comparable to a standalone release.
